[1] Saudi Arabia, 4 new cases 18-30 Oct 2017
Date: Mon 30 Oct 2017
Source: Saudi MOH 18-30 Oct 2017 [edited]
http://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/default.aspx?PageIndex=1?


As of Mon 30 Oct 2017, there have been a total of:
1730 laboratory-confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection, including
699 deaths [reported case fatality rate 40.4 percent],
1014 recoveries, and
14 currently active cases/infections.

[As previously mentioned, the numbers of deaths, recoveries, and currently active cases come from my spreadsheet tallies and differ from those listed on the Saudi MOH website; my spreadsheet counts asymptomatic infections as they are reported. One complication is the reporting of cases as either recoveries or deaths that cannot be confirmed as previously reported newly confirmed cases. - Mod.MPP]

Since the last ProMED-mail update [17 Oct 2017], there have been a total of:
4 newly confirmed cases,
0 newly reported fatality, and
1 newly reported recovery.

Information on newly confirmed cases (4 cases):
30 Oct 2017 (1 new case)
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2017-10-30-001.aspx

1 - A 76-year-old Saudi female, non-healthcare worker from Taif [Makkah region] currently in stable condition. Classified as a primary case with a history of indirect contact with camels in the 14 days preceding onset of illness.

29 Oct 2017 (1 new case)
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2017-10-29-001.aspx

2 - A 59-year-old Saudi male, non-healthcare worker from Taif [Makkah region] currently in critical condition. Classified as a primary case with a history of direct contact with camels in the 14 days preceding onset of illness.

27 Oct 2017 (1 new case)
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2017-10-27-001.aspx

3 - A 36-year-old Saudi male, non-healthcare worker from Hufoof [Ash Sharqīyah region] currently in stable condition. Classified as a primary case with high risk exposure history in the 14 days preceding onset of illness still under investigation.

26 Oct 2017 (1 new case)
https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/PressReleases/Pages/statistics-2017-10-26-001.aspx

4 - A 56-year-old Saudi male, non-healthcare worker from Tabuk [Tabūk region] currently in critical condition. Classified as a primary case with a history of direct contact with camels in the 14 days preceding onset of illness.

